Numeric functions.

Beyond the obvious arithmetic, the function library carries a handful of numeric helpers that earn their place in financial work.

The rounding family is the interesting one. There is ceiling, which rounds up to the next integer, and floor, which rounds down. There is round, which rounds half up to a number of decimal places. And there is b-round, which is banker's rounding — it rounds a half to the nearest even number instead of always up.

That banker's rounding detail matters more than it sounds. When you sum millions of rounded amounts, always rounding halves upward introduces a steady upward bias. Rounding halves to even cancels that bias out over many values, which is exactly why accounting systems prefer it.

Two more worth knowing are greatest and least. They work row-wise across several columns — greatest returns the largest value among the columns for each row, least the smallest. These are perfect for caps and floors. You can floor a principal amount at fifty thousand with greatest, and cap it at two million with least, all without a single conditional expression.
